The Meru High Court has extended interim orders suspending the impeachment Motion against Wajir Governor Mohamed Abdi.  Justice Edward Muriithi extended the orders barring the Senate and its Speaker Kenneth Lusaka from proceeding with the impeachment Motion until the case filed under a certificate of urgency is heard on May 20.  “It is hereby ordered that the petitioner serves hard copy set of the full documents in the petition and the application upon all parties by May 4. Respondents to file their responses within 14 days of service,” Justice Muriithi said. The case by six people against the governor was filed through lawyers Kiogora Mugambi, Mwangi Ndegwa and Ndegwa Njiru.  Lawyer Ahmednasir Abdullahi is representing the county assembly and its speaker.  On Friday last week, Justice Muriithi ordered for a status quo to the effect that Mr Lusaka and the Senate do not proceed to debate any Motion of impeachment related to county assembly resolutions of April 27.  Wajir governor ouster bid linked to Ruto and 2022 succession  Lusaka calls special sitting to hear Wajir Governor impeachment motion  Tana River MCAs impeach Speaker Justin Nkaduda   Impeaching Ruto would be a bad idea The residents have termed the Motion incompetent, irregular, illegal, a violation to Kenyan constitution and defective.     Badhii ya wakilishi wa wadi waleta mjadala ya kumn’gatua mamlakani gavana Issac Ruto  Alfred Keter to continue with his impeachment motion  How Governor Wa Iria escaped impeachment By Brian Otieno | 1 hour ago By Moses Nyamori and Kepher Otieno | 1 hour ago By Moses Nyamori | 1 hour ago By Standard Team | 5 hours ago Read The Standard uninterrupted with no advertisements